
[1]calcination

   CALCINATION, n. [from calcine.]

   1. The operation of expelling from a substance by heat, some volatile
   matter with which it is combined, or which is the cementing principle,
   and thus reducing it to a friable state. Thus chalk and carbonate of
   lime are reduced to lime by calcination, or the expulsion of carbonic
   acid.

   2. The operation of reducing a metal to an oxyd, or metallic calx. This
   is modern chemistry is called oxidation.
